_Further reading_

* Cringely, Robert X.; Gau, John; and Segaller, Stephen for Oregon Public Broadcasting. 1998. "Nerds 2.0.1: A Brief History of the Internet." [http://www.pbs.org/opb/nerds2.0.1/](http://www.pbs.org/opb/nerds2.0.1/)
* Naughton, John (2000). _A Brief History of the Future: Origins of the Internet._ Phoenix. ISBN 075381093X
* Naughton, John. 2011. From Gutenberg to Zuckerberg: What You Really Need to Know About the Internet. Quercus.
* Castells, Manuel. 2003. The Internet Galaxy: Reflections on the Internet, Business, and Society. Oxford University Press.
* Abbate, Janet. 2000. Inventing the Internet. MIT Press.
* Stoll, Clifford. 1989. [The Cuckoo's Egg](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Cuckoo%27s_Egg). New York: Doubleday. ISBN 0-370-31433-6
* Hafner, Katie, Lyon, Matthew, Where Wizards Stay Up Late: The Origins Of The Internet. Simon & Schuster (1998), 304 p., ISBN-10: 0684832674
** Searchable preview: [http://books.google.com/books?id=RLKxSvCBQZcC&printsec=frontcover](http://books.google.com/books?id=RLKxSvCBQZcC&printsec=frontcover)
** Companion website to the book: [http://www.chick.net/wizards/](http://www.chick.net/wizards/)
* Standage, Tom (2007). The Victorian Internet: The Remarkable Story of the Telegraph and the Nineteenth Century's On-line Pioneers. Walker & Company.
* Sterling, B. 1994. The Hacker Crackdown (http://altfactor.ath.cx/library/stuff/hc.2/hc-en-00.html) - Free book on the hacking of phone networks and early prosecutions for cyber crime.

